You cannot pass the tags directly to the `runner` class. When you run the `junit` `runner` class, before executing any code, it loads all `cucumber.options` so parameterizing the `tags` in `runner` class is not possible. You can pass tags from command line, please refer this [solution][1].


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37841594/cucumber-tags-options-from-command-line

Alternatively you can use `junit.runner.JUnitCore` to execute the `junit` classes. Let&#39;s see an example,

**Step#1**:  You need to have a `main` method to execute the code as java program not as junit test. 

    import org.junit.internal.TextListener;
    import org.junit.runner.JUnitCore;
    
    public class Main {
    	public static void main(String[] args) {
    		System.setProperty(&quot;cucumber.options&quot;, &quot;--tags @Login&quot;); //You can use the tag what you are reading from excel here.
    		JUnitCore junit = new JUnitCore();
    		junit.addListener(new TextListener(System.out));
    		junit.run(Runner.class);
    	}
    }

**Step#2**: Remove `tags` option from `Runner` class.

    @RunWith(Cucumber.class)
    @CucumberOptions(features = &quot;src\\test\\resources\\Features&quot;, glue = { &quot;code&quot; })
    public class Runner {
    
    }

**Step#3**: Run your `main` method.

**Feature file**:

    Feature: Application
    
      @Login
      Scenario: Login
        Given Login to the application
    
      @Logout
      Scenario: Login
        Given Logout from the application

**Step definition**:

    public class StepDefs {
    
    	@Given(&quot;^Login to the application$&quot;)
    	public void login() {
    		System.out.println(&quot;Logged into the application&quot;);
    	}
    
    	@Given(&quot;^Logout from the application$&quot;)
    	public void logout() {
    		System.out.println(&quot;Logged out from the application&quot;);
    	}
    }

**Output**:

