I had similar issue, where after some debugging and testing the &quot;tests&quot;:

* `onActivity` is called after my Activity&#39;s `onCreate(...)`.
* Said `onCreate(...)` launches a background-thread, which based on conditions, would call said Activity&#39;s `finish()`.
* Finally, `onActivity` is never called if the Activity&#39;s `finish()` is called before it.

The error may say &quot;destroyed&quot;, but `onActivity`&#39;s docs say that it even throws if Activity&#39;s &quot;finishing&quot; or &quot;finished&quot;.

Which was a surprise, as my test was all about checking if `finish()` is called after setting the right property of the Activity.

## Solutions

Solution A; I un-deprecated `ActivityTestRule`, which as you may already know, is no big deal and is what the well known AndroidX library does all the time for Android&#39;s API (not it&#39;s own API).

Get **`ActivityTestRule.java`** file from:\
https://gist.github.com/top-master/2127623cd837df9a9633714c44a56e16

Solution B; in your Activity add and use something like:
```
protected void finishSafely() {
    if (MyApp.isTestRun()) {
        MyApp.triggerTestHook(&quot;MyActivity:finishing&quot;);
    } else {
        finish();
    }
}
```
&gt;Where you need to decide how to implement `isTestRun()` and `triggerTestHook(...)` methods (where their names explain what they do).

