No.  The `BigDecimal` class provides no representation for NaN, +∞ or -∞.

You could consider using `null` ... except that you need at least&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; three distinct values to represent NaN, +∞ or -∞, and that is not possible with `null`.

You could consider creating a subclass of `BigDecimal` that handles these &quot;special&quot; values.

You could consider implementing your &quot;numbers&quot; as a wrapper for `BigDecimal`, and treat `NaN` and the like as special cases; e.g.

    public class MyNumber {
        private BigDecimal value;
        private boolean isNaN;
        ...

        private MyNumber(BigDecimal value, boolean isNaN) {
            this.value = value;
            this.isNaN = isNan;
        }

        public MyNumber multiply(MyNumber other) {
            if (this.isNaN || other.isNaN) {
                return new MyNumber(null, true);
            } else {
                return new MyNumber(this.value.multiply(other.value), false);
            }
        }

        // etcetera
    }

(The above is illustrative only.  I would implement it differently.)

